R Markdown essentials

We will consider three essential elements of R Markdown in this workshop:

  • YAML
  • Markdown text
  • Code chunks

YAML

The YAML ("YAML ain't markup language" or "Yet another markup language") is 
the document information stored at top the R Markdown document, bounded on 
each end by `---`. When you first create a new .Rmd, that will 
look something like this:

    ---
    title: "Document title"
    author: "Author"
    date: "YYYY-MM-DD"
    output: html_document
    ---

Markdown text

Most stuff that is outside of the YAML and code chunks in our .Rmd is our text in markdown.

  • * italic
  • ** bold
  • *** bold italic

Code chunks

Code chunks are where we'll add most code in an R Markdown document 
(though we'll see later we can also add or refer to R code inline). 
There are a number of ways to add a code chunk, including:

-   Click on the green `+ c` button in the top bar for the .Rmd, 
then choose `R` (or explore options for adding code in other languages)

-   In the menu, click Code \> Insert Chunk

-   Use the shortcut (Ctrl + Alt + I)

-   Just type in the start and end gates (\`\`\``{r}` to start, \`\`\` to end)

Chunk options: common settings

  • warning
  • messages
  • echo
  • include
  • error
  • output
  • you can set options globally
knitr::opts_chunk$set(echo = FALSE)

R Markdown customization - 1

  • toc: true: add a table of contents based on header hierarchies
  • toc_float: true: make it a floating TOC
  • number_sections: true: add numbered sections based on header hierarchy
  • theme: _____: add a bootstrap theme
  • code_folding: hide: code is default hidden, but available if the reader clicks on the ‘Code’ button created

R Markdown customization - 2

---
title: "First R Markdown document"
subtitle: "How to customize YAML"
author: "Chuck Norris"
output: 
  html_document:
    theme: flatly
    toc: true
    toc_float: true
    number_sections: true
    code_folding: hide
---

Table of content

  • title: “Chart”

  • output:

     -html_document:

       -toc: true

       - toc_depth: 2

Floating table content

output: 
  html_document: 
    toc: yes
    toc_float: TRUE

Referencing to variable outside of the chunk

  • using ` name of the chunk and variable name
meanmpg<-paste(" ",round(mean(mtcars$mpg, na.rm = TRUE),2))

-The mean mpg is 20.09.

Sourcing scripts

Sometimes, you’ll want to incorporate something from an R script into an R Markdown document. This might be the case if you have long code, and you might want it to exist in a script instead of cluttering up your .Rmd.

    source("your-script.R", local = knitr::knit_global())

Caching code chunks

If you have a code chunk that is really time consuming (e.g. reading in big datasets, running simulations, etc.), then you may want to cache that code chunk. That means that when you knit your .Rmd, instead of running every code chunk from the top down, it will avoid running a cached code chunk if there are no changes from the previously knit version.

```{r, cache = TRUE}
ggplot(data = diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point()
```

Parameters

  • define parameters in YAML
---
title: "First R Markdown document"
subtitle: "How to customize YAML"
author: "Chuck Norris"
output: 
  html_document:
    theme: flatly
    toc: true
    toc_float: true
    number_sections: true
    code_folding: hide
params:
  dataset: "airquality"
  temp: 40
---
```{r}
library(skimr)

skim(get(params$dataset))
subset(get(params$dataset),params$temp<Temp)
```

Making dynamic headings

```{r}

x<-c("A","B","C")

for (element in x) {

      cat('\n###',element, '\n')
        
        print(element)
    
        cat('\n')
  
}

```
